\u00f0r\u00f8\u00f0r \u00d3l\u00e1fsson}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou |[[Crovan dynasty]]|||10 November|1187}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[\u00d3l\u00e1fr Gu\u00f0r\u00f8\u00f0arson (died 1153)|\u00d3l\u00e1fr Gu\u00f0r\u00f8\u00f0arson]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[King of the Isles]] |years=1153/1154\u20131156}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Somairle mac Gilla Brigte]]<sup>1</sup>|after2=[[Dubgall mac Somairle]]}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[R\u01ebgnvaldr \u00d3l\u00e1fsson (fl. 1164)|R\u01ebgnvaldr \u00d3l\u00e1fsson]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[King of the Isles]] |years=1164\u20131187}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[R\u01ebgnvaldr Gu\u00f0r\u00f8\u00f0arson]]}}\n{{s-ref |Either Somairle or Dubgall gained the kingship from Gu\u00f0r\u00f8\u00f0r in 1156. Whilst it is possible that Dubgall was the nominal monarch, it is evident that the real power was possessed by Somairle, and Irish sources certainly regarded the latter as king later in his career.}}\n{{Dublin Monarchs}}\n{{Kings of the Isles}}\n{{Scandinavian Scotland|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gudrodr Olafsson}}\n[[Category:1187 deaths]]\n[[Category:12th-century monarchs in Europe]]\n[[Category:12th-century Irish monarchs]]\n[[Category:12th-century rulers of the Kingdom of the Isles]]\n[[Category:Burials in Iona]]\n[[Category:Crovan dynasty]]\n[[Category:Monarchs of Dublin]]\n[[Category:Monarchs of the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Rulers of the Kingdom of the Isles]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gu%C3%B0r%C3%B8%C3%B0r_%C3%93l%C3%A1fsson"}
{"title_page": "Julius Leigh Jacobsen", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox chess biography\n| name        = Julius Leigh Jacobsen\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| full_name   = \n| country     = [[Australia]]\n| birth_date  = {{start date|1862|05|28|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[England]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1916|06|01|1862|05|28|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Royal Prince Alfred Hospital]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n| title       = Australian Chess Champion (1897)\n| worldchampion = \n| womensworldchampion = \n| ICCFworldchampion =\n| rating      = \n| peakrating  = \n| ranking     = \n| peakranking = \n| FideID      =\n}}\n\n'''Julius Leigh Jacobsen''' (28 May 1862 \u2013 1 June 1916) was an English-born, Australian chess player who won the [[Australian Chess Championship]] in 1897 and the [[New South Wales]] Championship in 1901.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gambiter.com/chess/tournaments/Australian_chess_championship.html |title=Australian Chess Championship |website=Gambiter |language=en |access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.auschess.org.au/columns/smh/smh020701.htm |title=Sydney Morning-Herald Chess Column |website=Australian Chess Federation |access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chesskids.com.au/wp-content/uploads/pdf/knight-times/chess-kids-0601.pdf |title=Australian Chess History |last=Wright |first=Antony |date=May 2006|page=5}}</ref> He was also the tutor of [[William Samuel Viner]], who later became the Australian Chess Champion himself.<ref name=smh>{{Cite web |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article15665263 |title=DEATH OF MR. J. L. JACOBSEN. |date=1916-06-03 |website=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954) |pages=10 |access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Chess career==\nJacobsen's chess prowess first came to public attention when he was fourteen, when he defeated some very strong English players, leading [[Wilhelm Steinitz]] to dub him the \"boy prodigy\".<ref name=smh/><ref name=news>{{Cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article163799588 |title=The Chess Champion of Australasia |date=1897-12-25 |work=Sydney Mail and New South Wales Advertiser (NSW : 1871 - 1912) |access-date=2018-01-22 |pages=1360}}</ref> At the age of sixteen, he defeated [[Henry Bird (chess player)|Henry Bird]] (+4 -2 =1) in an April 1879 match. He then stopped playing chess and moved to [[South Africa]] the following year; he arrived in Australia about six years later. In Australia, he resumed playing chess and became the country's national champion in 1897.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U2n7DAAAQBAJ |title=H.E. Bird: A Chess Biography with 1,198 Games |last=Renette |first=Hans |date=2016-09-23 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9781476624624 |pages=245 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\nAn article published in ''[[the Sydney Mail]]'' in 1897, shortly after Jacobsen's victory in that year's Australian Chess Championship, stated that \"His style of play is very attractive to onlookers, and his chess combinations are rapidly conceived and brilliantly executed.\"<ref name=news/> His obituary in the ''[[Sydney Morning-Herald]]'' said that his \"...style was extremely brilliant, and he played rapidly even in complicated positions.\"<ref name=smh/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Chessgames player|126907}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacobsen, Julius Leigh}}\n[[Category:Australian chess players]]\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kingston upon Hull]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to South Africa]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:19th-century chess players]]\n\n\n{{Australia-chess-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox chess biography\n| name        = Julius Leigh Jacobsen\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| full_name   = \n| country     = [[Australia]]\n| birth_date  = {{start date|1862|05|28|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[England]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1916|06|01|1862|05|28|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Royal Prince Alfred Hospital]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n| title       = Australian Chess Champion (1897)\n| worldchampion = \n| womensworldchampion = \n| ICCFworldchampion =\n| rating      = \n| peakrating  = \n| ranking     = \n| peakranking = \n| FideID      =\n}}\n\n'''Julius Leigh Jacobsen''' (28 May 1862 \u2013 1 June 1916) was an English-born Australian chess player who won the [[Australian Chess Championship]] in 1897 and the [[New South Wales]] Championship in 1901.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gambiter.com/chess/tournaments/Australian_chess_championship.html |title=Australian Chess Championship |website=Gambiter |language=en |access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.auschess.org.au/columns/smh/smh020701.htm |title=Sydney Morning-Herald Chess Column |website=Australian Chess Federation |access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chesskids.com.au/wp-content/uploads/pdf/knight-times/chess-kids-0601.pdf |title=Australian Chess History |last=Wright |first=Antony |date=May 2006|page=5}}</ref> He was also the tutor of [[William Samuel Viner]], who later became the Australian Chess Champion himself.<ref name=smh>{{Cite web |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article15665263 |title=DEATH OF MR. J. L. JACOBSEN. |date=1916-06-03 |website=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954) |pages=10 |access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Chess career==\nJacobsen's chess prowess first came to public attention when he was fourteen, when he defeated some very strong English players, leading [[Wilhelm Steinitz]] to dub him the \"boy prodigy\".<ref name=smh/><ref name=news>{{Cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article163799588 |title=The Chess Champion of Australasia |date=1897-12-25 |work=Sydney Mail and New South Wales Advertiser (NSW : 1871 - 1912) |access-date=2018-01-22 |pages=1360}}</ref> At the age of sixteen, he defeated [[Henry Bird (chess player)|Henry Bird]] (+4 -2 =1) in an April 1879 match. He then stopped playing chess and moved to [[South Africa]] the following year; he arrived in Australia about six years later. In Australia, he resumed playing chess and became the country's national champion in 1897.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U2n7DAAAQBAJ |title=H.E. Bird: A Chess Biography with 1,198 Games |last=Renette |first=Hans |date=2016-09-23 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9781476624624 |pages=245 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\nAn article published in ''[[the Sydney Mail]]'' in 1897, shortly after Jacobsen's victory in that year's Australian Chess Championship, stated that \"His style of play is very attractive to onlookers, and his chess combinations are rapidly conceived and brilliantly executed.\"<ref name=news/> His obituary in the ''[[Sydney Morning-Herald]]'' said that his \"...style was extremely brilliant, and he played rapidly even in complicated positions.\"<ref name=smh/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Chessgames player|126907}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacobsen, Julius Leigh}}\n[[Category:Australian chess players]]\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kingston upon Hull]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to South Africa]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:19th-century chess players]]\n\n\n{{Australia-chess-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tchouppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julius_Leigh_Jacobsen"}
{"title_page": "Caught in the Web", "text_new": "{{short description|2012 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Caught in the Web\n| image          = Caught in the Web poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Chen Kaige]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Gao Yuanyuan]]<br>[[Mark Chao]]<br>[[Yao Chen]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2012|7|6|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = China\n| language       = Mandarin\n}}\n\n'''''Caught in the Web''''' ({{zh|c=\u641c\u7d22|p=S\u014dusu\u01d2}}) is a 2012 Chinese [[drama film]] directed by [[Chen Kaige]]. In September 2012 it screened as a special presentation at the [[2012 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/tiff/2012/caughtintheweb | title = Caught In The Web | date = 12 September 2012 | publisher = [[Toronto International Film Festival]] | access-date = 1 October 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120928110112/http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/tiff/2012/caughtintheweb# | archive-date = 28 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The film was selected as the Chinese entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Oscar]] at the [[85th Academy Awards]], but it did not make the final shortlist.<ref name=\"Oscar\">{{cite news |url=http://chinesefilms.cn/141/2012/09/29/122s12132.htm |title=''Caught in the Web'' Competes for Academy Awards |date=29 September 2012 |accessdate=29 September 2012 |work=Chinese Films |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009050715/http://www.chinesefilms.cn/141/2012/09/29/122s12132.htm |archivedate=9 October 2012  }}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSet in Hangzhou, in modern-day China, a young woman becomes embroiled in controversy after a cell phone video of her being disrespectful on a public bus to an elderly person goes viral. The aftermath affects her personal and professional life and brings her face to face with the video's poster, an ambitious journalist.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Gao Yuanyuan]] as Ye Lanqiu\n* [[Yao Chen]] as Chen Ruoxi\n* [[Mark Chao]] as Yang Shoucheng\n* [[Wang Xueqi]] as Shen Liushu\n* [[Chen Hong (actress)|Chen Hong]] as Mo Xiaoyu\n* [[Wang Luodan]] as Yang Jiaqi\n* Chen Ran as Tang Xiaohua\n* [[Zhang Yi (actor)|Zhang Yi]] as Zhang Mu\n* [[Tan Songyun]]\n\n==Reception==\nDerek Elley of ''[[Film Business Asia]]'' gave the film a score of 9/10, and states \"Chen has come late in the game to dealing with the social and ethical contradictions of life in modern-day China, but ''Web'' more than makes up for lost time. Densely plotted across its two hours' running-time, the film starts as a black comedy on the destructive power of modern media (especially China's internet discussion boards) but from its midway point gradually morphs into a complex web of love and ambition, both gained and lost.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.filmbiz.asia/reviews/caught-in-the-web|title=Caught in the Web|author=Elley, Derek|magazine=[[Film Business Asia]]|date=15 July 2012|access-date=21 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120080834/http://www.filmbiz.asia/reviews/caught-in-the-web#|archive-date=20 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMaggie Lee of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' describes it as \"An engrossing, if lengthy social drama in which a woman's minor public misconduct plunges her into a dragnet of cyber witch-hunting that unseats relationships, careers and a business empire, the punningly titled \"Caught in the Web\" reps a thought-provoking, character-driven morality tale by Chinese helmer Chen Kaige.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117948312/|title=Caught in the Web|author=Lee, Maggie|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=12 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nDeborah Young of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' states \"Chen Kaige's fast-paced contemporary dramedy is a masterful take on Internet character assassination.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/caught-web-toronto-review-371066|title=Caught in the Web: Toronto Review|author=Young, Deborah|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nDan Fainaru of ''[[Screen Daily]]'' describes the film as \"A cinematic tour de force in every respect, Che Kaige\u2019s complex, multi-layered story looks for a while like a satirical take on the misuse of new fancy gadgetry to deprive individuals of their last shred of privacy and ends on an introspective tone, suggesting there is no use blaming the gadgets, but the people behind them.\"<ref name=Fainaru>{{cite news|url=http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/the-latest/caught-in-the-web/5046707.article|title=Caught In The Web|author=Fainaru, Dan|work=[[Screen Daily]]|date=14 September 2012}}</ref>  Fainaru further describes the film as \"A surprisingly refreshing departure for one of China's leading Fifth Generation filmmakers, better identified with period pieces.\"<ref name=Fainaru/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 85th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Chinese submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[Human flesh search engine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2259360|Caught in the Web}}\n\n{{Chen Kaige |state=collapsed}}\n{{Chinese submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caught In The Web}}\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2012 drama films]]\n[[Category:Chinese films]]\n[[Category:Chinese drama films]]\n[[Category:Mandarin-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Chen Kaige]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2012 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Caught in the Web\n| image          = Caught in the Web poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Chen Kaige]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Gao Yuanyuan]]<br>[[Mark Chao]]<br>[[Yao Chen]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2012|7|6|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = China\n| language       = Mandarin\n}}\n\n'''''Caught in the Web''''' ({{zh|c=\u641c\u7d22|p=S\u014dusu\u01d2}}) is a 2012 Chinese [[drama film]] directed by [[Chen Kaige]]. In September 2012 it screened as a special presentation at the [[2012 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/tiff/2012/caughtintheweb | title = Caught In The Web | date = 12 September 2012 | publisher = [[Toronto International Film Festival]] | access-date = 1 October 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120928110112/http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/tiff/2012/caughtintheweb# | archive-date = 28 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The film was selected as the Chinese entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Oscar]] at the [[85th Academy Awards]], but it did not make the final shortlist.<ref name=\"Oscar\">{{cite news |url=http://chinesefilms.cn/141/2012/09/29/122s12132.htm |title=''Caught in the Web'' Competes for Academy Awards |date=29 September 2012 |accessdate=29 September 2012 |work=Chinese Films |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009050715/http://www.chinesefilms.cn/141/2012/09/29/122s12132.htm |archivedate=9 October 2012  }}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSet in Hangzhou, in modern-day China, a young woman becomes embroiled in controversy after a cell phone video of her being disrespectful on a public bus to an elderly person goes viral. The aftermath affects her personal and professional life and brings her face to face with the video's poster, an ambitious journalist.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Gao Yuanyuan]] as Ye Lanqiu\n* [[Yao Chen]] as Chen Ruoxi\n* [[Mark Chao]] as Yang Shoucheng\n* [[Wang Xueqi]] as Shen Liushu\n* [[Chen Hong (actress)|Chen Hong]] as Mo Xiaoyu\n* [[Wang Luodan]] as Yang Jiaqi\n* Chen Ran as Tang Xiaohua\n* [[Zhang Yi (actor)|Zhang Yi]] as Zhang Mu\n* [[Tan Songyun]]\n\n==Reception==\nDerek Elley of ''[[Film Business Asia]]'' gave the film a score of 9/10, and states \"Chen has come late in the game to dealing with the social and ethical contradictions of life in modern-day China, but ''Web'' more than makes up for lost time. Densely plotted across its two hours' running-time, the film starts as a black comedy on the destructive power of modern media (especially China's internet discussion boards) but from its midway point gradually morphs into a complex web of love and ambition, both gained and lost.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.filmbiz.asia/reviews/caught-in-the-web|title=Caught in the Web|author=Elley, Derek|magazine=[[Film Business Asia]]|date=15 July 2012|access-date=21 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120080834/http://www.filmbiz.asia/reviews/caught-in-the-web#|archive-date=20 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMaggie Lee of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' describes it as \"An engrossing, if lengthy social drama in which a woman's minor public misconduct plunges her into a dragnet of cyber witch-hunting that unseats relationships, careers and a business empire, the punningly titled \"Caught in the Web\" reps a thought-provoking, character-driven morality tale by Chinese helmer Chen Kaige.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117948312/|title=Caught in the Web|author=Lee, Maggie|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=12 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nDeborah Young of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' states \"Chen Kaige's fast-paced contemporary dramedy is a masterful take on Internet character assassination.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/caught-web-toronto-review-371066|title=Caught in the Web: Toronto Review|author=Young, Deborah|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nDan Fainaru of ''[[Screen Daily]]'' describes the film as \"A cinematic tour de force in every respect, Che Kaige\u2019s complex, multi-layered story looks for a while like a satirical take on the misuse of new fancy gadgetry to deprive individuals of their last shred of privacy and ends on an introspective tone, suggesting there is no use blaming the gadgets, but the people behind them.\"<ref name=Fainaru>{{cite news|url=http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/the-latest/caught-in-the-web/5046707.article|title=Caught In The Web|author=Fainaru, Dan|work=[[Screen Daily]]|date=14 September 2012}}</ref>  Fainaru further describes the film as \"A surprisingly refreshing departure for one of China's leading Fifth Generation filmmakers, better identified with period pieces.\"<ref name=Fainaru/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 85th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Chinese submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[Human flesh search engine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2259360|Caught in the Web}}\n\n{{Chen Kaige |state=collapsed}}\n{{Chinese submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caught In The Web}}\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2012 drama films]]\n[[Category:Chinese films]]\n[[Category:Chinese drama films]]\n[[Category:Mandarin-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Chen Kaige]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caught_in_the_Web"}
{"title_page": "Kanzimbe Solar Power Station", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox power station\n| name                = Kanzimbe Solar Power Station\n| name_official       = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| image_caption       = \n| image_alt           = \n| location_map        = Malawi\n| coordinates ={{coord|13|46|20|S|34|29|21|E|type:landmark| display=inline,title}}\n| country             = [[Malawi]]\n| location            = Kanzimbe, [[Salima District]]\n| status              = UC\n| construction_began  = December 2018\n| commissioned        = 2021 Expected\n| decommissioned      = \n| cost                = \n| owner               = JCM Matswana Solar Energy\n| operator            = \n| solar_type             = PV\n| ps_site_area        = \n| ps_units_operational   = \n| ps_units_manu_model    = \n| ps_units_uc            = \n| ps_units_planned       = \n| ps_units_cancelled     = \n| ps_units_decommissioned= \n| thermal_capacity       = \n| ps_electrical_capacity = {{convert|60|MW}}\n| ps_electrical_cap_fac  = \n| ps_annual_generation   = \n| website                = \n| extra                  = \n}}\n\n'''Kanzimbe Solar Power Station''', is a {{convert|60|MW}} [[Solar power|solar]] power plant, under construction, in [[Malawi]], in [[Southern Africa]].<ref name=\"1R\">{{cite web|date=4 December 2018 |url=https://www.esi-africa.com/malawi-60mw-solar-plant-to-end-blackouts/ |title=Malawi: 60MW solar plant to end blackouts | access-date=8 December 2018 |publisher=ESI-Africa |author=ESI-Africa |location=Rondebosch, South Africa}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe power station would be located in the neighborhood known as Kanzimbe, in [[Salima District]], on the south-western banks of [[Lake Malawi]],<ref name=\"2R\">{{google maps| url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Salima,+Malawi/@-13.8953422,34.8235422,8z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x19200286b66b38a7:0x948217683e1baf9!8m2!3d-13.6809586!4d34.4198243 |title=Location of Salima District, Malawi |access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref> approximately {{convert|100|km|0}},<ref name=\"3R\">{{cite web| access-date=8 December 2018 |date=8 December 2018 |\nurl=https://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Malawi_Distance_Result.asp?vr=apes&fromplace=Lilongwe,%20Central%20Region,%20MWI&toplace=Kanzimbe,%20Salima,%20Central%20Region,%20MWI&fromplace=Lilongwe,%20Central%20Region,%20MWI&toplace=Kanzimbe,%20Salima,%20Central%20Region,%20MWI |title=Distance between Lilongwe, Central Region, MWI, Lilongwe, Central Region, MWI and Kanzimbe, Salima, Central Region, MWI, Kanzimbe, Salima, Central Region, MWI |\npublisher=Globefeed.com |author=Globefeed.com}}</ref> by road, north-east of [[Lilongwe]], Malawi's capital city.\n\n==Overview==\nAs of 2018, Malawi is reported to have the lowest electrification rate in the World, with a per capital consumption estimated at 93 kWh per year compared with an average of 432 kWh for Sub-Saharan Africa and 2167 kWh per year for the World average. There is urgency for Malawi to reach the critical threshold of 500 kWh per year.<ref name=\"4R\">{{cite journal |access-date=8 December 2018 |  url=http://www.scielo.org.za/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S1021-447X2015000200003 |title=Energy supply in Malawi: Options and issues: Current status of energy demand and supply in Malawi |date=May 2015 |journal=Journal of Energy in Southern Africa | format=Volume 26, number 2 | location=Cape Town |author=John L Taulo, Kenneth Joseph Gondwe, and Adoniya Ben Sebitosi}}</ref>\n \nAs part of efforts to increase electricity output and to diversify Malawi's sources of energy, the country is developing this solar power station (60 megawatts), [[Kammwamba Thermal Power Station]] (300 megawatts) and [[Mpatamanga Hydroelectric Power Station]] (350 megawatts), in the medium term.<ref name=\"5R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nyasatimes.com/mutharika-opens-solar-plant-construction-more-investments-to-end-blackouts-in-malawi/ |title=Mutharika Opens Solar Plant Construction: More Investments To End Blackouts In Malawi |newspaper=[[Nyasa Times]]  |last=Watson Maingo-Mana |first=and Green Muheya |date=3 December 2018 |access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe energy generated by his power station will be sold to the [[Electricity Supply Commission of Malawi]] (Escom), after the owner/developers conclude a power-purchase agreement.<ref name=\"6R\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maravipost.com/president-mutharika-opens-60-megawatts-solar-plant-construction/ | title=President Mutharika opens 60 megawatts solar plant construction |newspaper=Maravi Post Quoting [[Malawi News Agency]] |author=Malawi News Agency |date=4 December 2018 | access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Developers==\nThe power station is being developed by ''JCM Power'', the [[Canada|Canadian]] renewable energy, independent power producer, active in South Asia, Latin America and Sub-Saharan Africa.<ref name=\"5R\"/><ref name=\"7R\">{{cite web |access-date=8 December 2018 |url=https://jcmpower.ca/salima-malawi/ |publisher=JCMPower Canada |title=Salima, Malawi Solar Project: Project Overview |date=2018 |\nauthor=JCMPower Canada |location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\n==Construction timeline, costs and funding==\nConstruction was flagged off in December 2018.<ref name=\"5R\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of power stations in Malawi]]\n{{stack|{{Portal|Malawi|Renewable energy}}}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://venturesafrica.com/malawis-government-has-launched-the-construction-of-60-mw-solar-plant-as-it-seeks-solutions-to-its-power-problems/ Malawi's Government Has Launched The Construction Of 60 Megawatts Solar Plant As It Seeks Solutions To Its Power Problems]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kanzimbe Solar Power Station}}\n[[Category:Solar power stations in Malawi]]\n[[Category:Energy infrastructure in Malawi]]\n[[Category:Proposed solar power stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox power station\n| name                = Kanzimbe Solar Power Station\n| name_official       = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| image_caption       = \n| image_alt           = \n| location_map        = Malawi\n| coordinates ={{coord|13|46|20|S|34|29|21|E|type:landmark| display=inline,title}}\n| country             = [[Malawi]]\n| location            = Kanzimbe, [[Salima District]]\n| status              = UC\n| construction_began  = December 2018\n| commissioned        = 2021 Expected\n| decommissioned      = \n| cost                = \n| owner               = JCM Matswana Solar Energy\n| operator            = \n| solar_type             = PV\n| ps_site_area        = \n| ps_units_operational   = \n| ps_units_manu_model    = \n| ps_units_uc            = \n| ps_units_planned       = \n| ps_units_cancelled     = \n| ps_units_decommissioned= \n| thermal_capacity       = \n| ps_electrical_capacity = {{convert|60|MW}}\n| ps_electrical_cap_fac  = \n| ps_annual_generation   = \n| website                = \n| extra                  = \n}}\n\n'''Kanzimbe Solar Power Station''', is a {{convert|60|MW}} [[Solar power|solar]] power plant, under construction, in [[Malawi]], in [[Southern Africa]].<ref name=\"1R\">{{cite web|date=4 December 2018 |url=https://www.esi-africa.com/malawi-60mw-solar-plant-to-end-blackouts/ |title=Malawi: 60MW solar plant to end blackouts | access-date=8 December 2018 |publisher=ESI-Africa |author=ESI-Africa |location=Rondebosch, South Africa}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe power station would be located in the neighborhood known as Kanzimbe, in [[Salima District]], on the south-western banks of [[Lake Malawi]],<ref name=\"2R\">{{google maps| url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Salima,+Malawi/@-13.8953422,34.8235422,8z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x19200286b66b38a7:0x948217683e1baf9!8m2!3d-13.6809586!4d34.4198243 |title=Location of Salima District, Malawi |access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref> approximately {{convert|100|km|0}},<ref name=\"3R\">{{cite web| access-date=8 December 2018 |date=8 December 2018 |\nurl=https://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Malawi_Distance_Result.asp?vr=apes&fromplace=Lilongwe,%20Central%20Region,%20MWI&toplace=Kanzimbe,%20Salima,%20Central%20Region,%20MWI&fromplace=Lilongwe,%20Central%20Region,%20MWI&toplace=Kanzimbe,%20Salima,%20Central%20Region,%20MWI |title=Distance between Lilongwe, Central Region, MWI, Lilongwe, Central Region, MWI and Kanzimbe, Salima, Central Region, MWI, Kanzimbe, Salima, Central Region, MWI |\npublisher=Globefeed.com |author=Globefeed.com}}</ref> by road, north-east of [[Lilongwe]], Malawi's capital city.\n\n==Overview==\nAs of 2018, Malawi is reported to have the lowest electrification rate in the World, with a per capital consumption estimated at 93 kWh per year compared with an average of 432 kWh for Sub-Saharan Africa and 2167 kWh per year for the World average. There is urgency for Malawi to reach the critical threshold of 500 kWh per year.<ref name=\"4R\">{{cite journal |access-date=8 December 2018 |  url=http://www.scielo.org.za/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S1021-447X2015000200003 |title=Energy supply in Malawi: Options and issues: Current status of energy demand and supply in Malawi |date=May 2015 |journal=Journal of Energy in Southern Africa | format=Volume 26, number 2 | location=Cape Town |author=John L Taulo, Kenneth Joseph Gondwe, and Adoniya Ben Sebitosi}}</ref>\n \nAs part of efforts to increase electricity output and to diversify Malawi's sources of energy, the country is developing this solar power station (60 megawatts), [[Kammwamba Thermal Power Station]] (300 megawatts) and [[Mpatamanga Hydroelectric Power Station]] (350 megawatts), in the medium term.<ref name=\"5R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nyasatimes.com/mutharika-opens-solar-plant-construction-more-investments-to-end-blackouts-in-malawi/ |title=Mutharika Opens Solar Plant Construction: More Investments To End Blackouts In Malawi |newspaper=[[Nyasa Times]]  |last=Watson Maingo-Mana |first=and Green Muheya |date=3 December 2018 |access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe energy generated by his power station will be sold to the [[Electricity Supply Commission of Malawi]] (Escom), after the owner/developers conclude a power-purchase agreement.<ref name=\"6R\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maravipost.com/president-mutharika-opens-60-megawatts-solar-plant-construction/ | title=President Mutharika opens 60 megawatts solar plant construction |newspaper=Maravi Post Quoting [[Malawi News Agency]] |author=Malawi News Agency |date=4 December 2018 | access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Developers==\nThe power station is being developed by ''JCM Power'', the [[Canada|Canadian]] renewable energy, independent power producer, active in South Asia, Latin America and Sub-Saharan Africa.<ref name=\"5R\"/><ref name=\"7R\">{{cite web |access-date=8 December 2018 |url=https://jcmpower.ca/salima-malawi/ |publisher=JCMPower Canada |title=Salima, Malawi Solar Project: Project Overview |date=2018 |\nauthor=JCMPower Canada |location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\n==Construction timeline, costs and funding==\nConstruction was flagged off in December 2018.<ref name=\"5R\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of power stations in Malawi]]\n{{stack|{{Portal|Malawi|Renewable energy}}}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://venturesafrica.com/malawis-government-has-launched-the-construction-of-60-mw-solar-plant-as-it-seeks-solutions-to-its-power-problems/ Malawi's Government Has Launched The Construction Of 60 Megawatts Solar Plant As It Seeks Solutions To Its Power Problems]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kanzimbe Solar Power Station}}\n[[Category:Solar power stations in Malawi]]\n[[Category:Proposed energy infrastructure]]\n[[Category:Energy infrastructure in Malawi]]\n", "name_user": "Macquaria", "label": "safe", "comment": "Category reorganization", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kanzimbe_Solar_Power_Station"}
{"title_page": "Galston High School", "text_new": "{{short description|Public school in Sydney, Australia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                = Galston High School\n| logo                = Galston High School badge.jpg\n| image =\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = \n| motto               = {{lang-la|Nitamur Neve Cedamus}}\n| motto_translation   = Let Us Strive And Not Yield\n| slogan              = Achieving Excellence \u2013 Inspiring Success \n| type                = [[Education in Australia#Government schools|Government-funded]] [[Mixed-sex school|co-educational]] [[Comprehensive school|comprehensive]] [[secondary school|secondary]] [[day school]]\n| educational_authority = [[Department of Education (New South Wales)|New South Wales Department of Education]]\n| district    = \n| established         = {{start date and age|1972|01|df=y}}<ref name=nswps>{{cite web|title=Galston High \u2013 Cumberland|url=https://nswgovschoolhistory.cese.nsw.gov.au/schoolHistory?schoolId=3191 |website=History of New South Wales government schools|publisher=NSW Department of Education|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref>\n| principal           = Jillian Tourlas\n| location            = [[Galston, New South Wales|Galston]], [[Hills District]], [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]\n| country             = Australia\n| coordinates         = {{coord|33|39|37|S|151|02|21|E|region:AU-NSW_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map             = Australia Sydney\n| pushpin_image           = \n| pushpin_mapsize         = 250\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in [[Sydney|greater metropolitan Sydney]]\n| pushpin_label           = \n| pushpin_label_position  = top\n|module                  = {{Infobox mapframe\n|stroke-colour           = #C60C30\n|stroke-width            = 3\n|marker                  = school\n|marker-colour           = #1F2F57\n|zoom                    = 13 }}\n| campus_type            = [[Suburban area|Semi-rural]]\n| grades = [[Year 7|7]]-[[Year 12|12]]\n| grades_label = Years\n| enrolment           = ~716<ref name=SchoolLocator>{{cite web |url=http://www.schools.nsw.edu.au/schoolfind/locator/?do=showRecord&code=8481 |title=Galston High School |accessdate=6 April 2011 |work=School Locator |publisher=NSW Public Schools}}</ref>\n| enrolment_as_of     = 2013\n| colours             = Teal and navy blue {{colorbox|teal}}{{colorbox|navy}}\n| homepage            = {{URL|galston-h.schools.nsw.edu.au/}}\n}}\n'''Galston High School''' is a [[Education in Australia#Government schools|government-funded]] [[Mixed-sex school|co-educational]] [[Comprehensive school|comprehensive]] [[secondary school|secondary]] [[day school]], located in [[Galston, New South Wales|Galston]], a suburb in the [[Hills District]] of [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia. \n\n==History==\nThe school site was previously owned by James David Waddell. His family bought the land in the 1840s and set up an orchard on what are now the school grounds.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} A cottage was built in 1867, now known as Waddell Cottage.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=1780571|title=Galston High School, Waddell Cottage an water trough &#124; NSW Environment & Heritage|website=www.environment.nsw.gov.au}}</ref> Waddell lived in the cottage until 1969, by when the house and orchard were in a bad state of repair. Waddell had refused to put in running water or have the electricity connected. Because he hadn't paid his taxes, the land was resumed by the government as it was thought to be an ideal location for a high school.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Local residents fought to have the cottage restored rather than demolished.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nGalston High School officially began in 1972, although the first classes were taught at Baulkham Hills High School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/the-hills/galston-high-celebrates-40th-year/news-story/0041860f68746a2c352a3c877f69be9b|title=Years of lessons learned at Galston High School|date=15 October 2014|website=www.dailytelegraph.com.au}}</ref> In 1974, the school's buildings opened on the current site and were added to until its final completion in 1982.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} The first HSC class to graduate was in 1977. The original school crest has the motto \"Nitamur Neve Cedamus\", which is taken from Lord Tennyson's ''Ulysses'' and translates as  \"Let us strive and not yield\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/45392/ulysses|title=Ulysses by Alfred, Lord Tennyson|date=1 July 2019|website=Poetry Foundation}}</ref>\n\nIn the early hours of 19 May 2014, Galston High School's library caught fire. This occurred from some technical difficulties in the electric wire systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://galston-h.schools.nsw.gov.au/gallery/the-fire.html|title=The Fire - Galston High School|website=galston-h.schools.nsw.gov.au}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Adam Berry (footballer)|Adam Berry]], footballer\n* [[Adam Wilkinson]], businessperson\n* [[Aden Young]], actor\n\n==Notable staff==\n* [[Elena Duggan]], winner of ''[[MasterChef Australia]]'' 2016\n* Jonathan Kim Sing, Most famous Youtuber in the world\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{portal|New South Wales|Schools}}}}\n* [[List of government schools in New South Wales]]\n* [[Education in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|http://www.galston-h.schools.nsw.edu.au}}\n* [https://education.nsw.gov.au/school-finder/ New South Wales Department of Education] \u2013 Galston High School\n\n{{High Schools in North Sydney}}\n{{Public high schools in New South Wales|state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:Hornsby Shire]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1972]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public school in Sydney, Australia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                = Galston High School\n| logo                = Galston High School badge.jpg\n| image =\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = \n| motto               = {{lang-la|Nitamur Neve Cedamus}}\n| motto_translation   = Let Us Strive And Not Yield\n| slogan              = Achieving Excellence \u2013 Inspiring Success \n| type                = [[Education in Australia#Government schools|Government-funded]] [[Mixed-sex school|co-educational]] [[Comprehensive school|comprehensive]] [[secondary school|secondary]] [[day school]]\n| educational_authority = [[Department of Education (New South Wales)|New South Wales Department of Education]]\n| district    = \n| established         = {{start date and age|1972|01|df=y}}<ref name=nswps>{{cite web|title=Galston High \u2013 Cumberland|url=https://nswgovschoolhistory.cese.nsw.gov.au/schoolHistory?schoolId=3191 |website=History of New South Wales government schools|publisher=NSW Department of Education|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref>\n| principal           = Jillian Tourlas\n| location            = [[Galston, New South Wales|Galston]], [[Hills District]], [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]\n| country             = Australia\n| coordinates         = {{coord|33|39|37|S|151|02|21|E|region:AU-NSW_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map             = Australia Sydney\n| pushpin_image           = \n| pushpin_mapsize         = 250\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in [[Sydney|greater metropolitan Sydney]]\n| pushpin_label           = \n| pushpin_label_position  = top\n|module                  = {{Infobox mapframe\n|stroke-colour           = #C60C30\n|stroke-width            = 3\n|marker                  = school\n|marker-colour           = #1F2F57\n|zoom                    = 13 }}\n| campus_type            = [[Suburban area|Semi-rural]]\n| grades = [[Year 7|7]]-[[Year 12|12]]\n| grades_label = Years\n| enrolment           = ~716<ref name=SchoolLocator>{{cite web |url=http://www.schools.nsw.edu.au/schoolfind/locator/?do=showRecord&code=8481 |title=Galston High School |accessdate=6 April 2011 |work=School Locator |publisher=NSW Public Schools}}</ref>\n| enrolment_as_of     = 2013\n| colours             = Teal and navy blue {{colorbox|teal}}{{colorbox|navy}}\n| homepage            = {{URL|galston-h.schools.nsw.edu.au/}}\n}}\n'''Galston High School''' is a [[Education in Australia#Government schools|government-funded]] [[Mixed-sex school|co-educational]] [[Comprehensive school|comprehensive]] [[secondary school|secondary]] [[day school]], located in [[Galston, New South Wales|Galston]], a suburb in the [[Hills District]] of [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia. \n\n==History==\nThe school site was previously owned by James David Waddell. His family bought the land in the 1840s and set up an orchard on what are now the school grounds.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} A cottage was built in 1867, now known as Waddell Cottage.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=1780571|title=Galston High School, Waddell Cottage an water trough &#124; NSW Environment & Heritage|website=www.environment.nsw.gov.au}}</ref> Waddell lived in the cottage until 1969, by when the house and orchard were in a bad state of repair. Waddell had refused to put in running water or have the electricity connected. Because he hadn't paid his taxes, the land was resumed by the government as it was thought to be an ideal location for a high school.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Local residents fought to have the cottage restored rather than demolished.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nGalston High School officially began in 1972, although the first classes were taught at Baulkham Hills High School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/the-hills/galston-high-celebrates-40th-year/news-story/0041860f68746a2c352a3c877f69be9b|title=Years of lessons learned at Galston High School|date=15 October 2014|website=www.dailytelegraph.com.au}}</ref> In 1974, the school's buildings opened on the current site and were added to until its final completion in 1982.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} The first HSC class to graduate was in 1977. The original school crest has the motto \"Nitamur Neve Cedamus\", which is taken from Lord Tennyson's ''Ulysses'' and translates as  \"Let us strive and not yield\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/45392/ulysses|title=Ulysses by Alfred, Lord Tennyson|date=1 July 2019|website=Poetry Foundation}}</ref>\n\nIn the early hours of 19 May 2014, Galston High School's library caught fire. This occurred from some technical difficulties in the electric wire systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://galston-h.schools.nsw.gov.au/gallery/the-fire.html|title=The Fire - Galston High School|website=galston-h.schools.nsw.gov.au}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Adam Berry (footballer)|Adam Berry]], footballer\n* [[Adam Wilkinson]], businessperson\n* [[Aden Young]], actor\n\n==Notable staff==\n* [[Elena Duggan]], winner of ''[[MasterChef Australia]]'' 2016\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{portal|New South Wales|Schools}}}}\n* [[List of government schools in New South Wales]]\n* [[Education in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|http://www.galston-h.schools.nsw.edu.au}}\n* [https://education.nsw.gov.au/school-finder/ New South Wales Department of Education] \u2013 Galston High School\n\n{{High Schools in North Sydney}}\n{{Public high schools in New South Wales|state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:Hornsby Shire]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1972]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8003:22d1:cf0